        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We propose to map the cluster A2390, at z=0.228, in CO(J=1-0) (rest
freq=115.2712 GHz) at 93.64 GHz. We ask for a resolution of 5 arcsec, in order
to observe possibly isolated and flocculent clouds. A rectangular region of 39
pointings (185 × 128 arcsec wide, corresponding to ~ 860 kpc × 592 kpc), will
cover the extended RC emission observed.

Requested sensitivity: Assuming, at first order, that the RC-CO relation holds
in cluster central regions, we determined from the radio continuum brightness,
the expected CO brightness for A2390 to be 2.7e10 Jy/sterad km/s. Assuming a
synthesized beam of 5 arcsec and a velocity width of 200 km/s, we estimate a line
peak of ~ 90 mJy/beam. To detect this signal at least 5 sigma level in a channel
width of 10 km/s, enough to resolve the line, a rms 18 mJy/beam, is needed. 
The OT estimates the time needed to execute the requested mosaic to be ~0.5 hours.

Correlator setup: We ask for the Frequency Division Mode of the correlator in
dual polarization (1875 MHz bandwidth) providing a spectral 
resolution which is more than enough for our purposes.
To reduce the data rate we selected a spectral averaging factor of 2 
(~3 km/s resolution).
Smoothing the channels to 10 km/s will allow us to accurately sample the line,
expected to be ~200 km/s wide, so we used this bandwidth to calculate the 
time needed to reach the required sensitivity. We centered the first baseband 
at the CO(1-0) frequency, and we located the remaining baseband to cover 
the entire band, in order to estimate the continuum.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
