    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>We ask for observations with ALMA in band 3 of the CO(1-0) transition in
two cooling-core clusters: A2029 and A2390. In these clusters the dominant
radio galaxy is surrounded by a very bright diffuse synchrotron emission
(mini-halo).
Mini-halos are puzzling radio sources and their origin is still uncertain.
In particular, the origin of the cosmic ray electrons in these synchrotron
sources is debated. In this proposal we want to study the possibility that
the mini-halo could be powered by a vast star formation event which may
represent the ultimate sink of the cooling flow material. If the process
of formation of massive stars proceeds as in ordinary star-forming
galaxies, we may expect the production of a high number of cosmic ray
electrons accelerated via SN explosions. If we will be able to confirm the
association between the presence of a bright mini-halo and the molecular
gas, this will be a strong indication that these enigmatic synchrotron
sources could be indeed powered by the star formation process originating
from the large scale cooling flow. The clusters A2029 and A2390 are the
best target to
investigate this problem being the brightest of sofar known mini-halos.</prp:abstract>
